abstract="Midori is an energy-efficient lightweight block cipher published by Banik et al. in ASIACRYPT 2015, which consists of two variants with block sizes of 64-bit and 128-bit, respectively. In this paper, a new method is proposed to exploit cell-oriented fault propagation patterns in recognizing appropriate faulty ciphertexts and fault positions, which poses a serious threat to practical security of Midori. In light of this, we present a Differential Fault Attack against the Midori using cell-oriented fault model. Specifically, by inducing two random cell faults into the input of the antepenultimate round, our attack reduces the secret key search space from                                                                                   {\$}{\$}2^{\{}128{\}}{\$}{\$}                                                                                            2                          128                                                                                     to                                                                                   {\$}{\$}2^{\{}32{\}}{\$}{\$}                                                                                            2                          32                                                                                     for Midori-128 and from                                                                                   {\$}{\$}2^{\{}128{\}}{\$}{\$}                                                                                            2                          128                                                                                     to                                                                                   {\$}{\$}2^{\{}80{\}}{\$}{\$}                                                                                            2                          80                                                                                     for Midori-64, respectively. Our experiments confirmed that two faulty ciphertexts induced into the input of antepenultimate round could recover twelve in sixteen cells of subkey with over 80{\%} probability.",
