pages="113--130",
abstract="Malleable signature schemes (                                                                          {\$}{\backslash}mathcal MSS{\$}                ) enable a third party to alter signed data in a controlled way, maintaining a valid signature after an authorized change. Most well studied cryptographic constructions are (1) redactable signatures (                                                                          {\$}{\backslash}mathcal RSS{\$}                ), and (2) sanitizable signatures (                                                                          {\$}{\backslash}mathcal SSS{\$}                ).                                                                           {\$}{\backslash}mathcal RSS{\$}                s allow the removal of blocks from a signed document, while                                                                           {\$}{\backslash}mathcal SSS{\$}                s allow changing blocks to arbitrary strings. We rigorously prove that                                                                           {\$}{\backslash}mathcal RSS{\$}                s are less expressive than                                                                           {\$}{\backslash}mathcal SSS{\$}                s: no unforgeable                                                                           {\$}{\backslash}mathcal RSS{\$}                 can be transformed into an                                                                           {\$}{\backslash}mathcal SSS{\$}                . For the opposite direction we give a black-box transformation of a single                                                                           {\$}{\backslash}mathcal SSS{\$}                , with tightened security, into an                                                                           {\$}{\backslash}mathcal RSS{\$}                .",
